                    <abstract lang="eng">Communicative listener feedback is a prevalent coordination mechanism in dialogue. Listeners use feedback to provide evidence of understanding to speakers, who, in turn, use it to reason about the listeners&apos; mental state of listening, determine the groundedness of communicated information, and adapt their subsequent utterances to the listeners&apos; needs. We describe a speaker-centric Bayesian model of listeners and their feedback behaviour, which can interpret the listener&apos;s feedback signal in its dialogue context and reason about the listener&apos;s mental state as well as the grounding status of objects in information state.</abstract>
